    <td width="44%" height="1" valign="top" align="left"><p align="left"><font
    face="Comic Sans MS"><strong><big><big>Lydia B</big></big></strong> is a Baba 30 designed<br>
    by Robert Perry and built in 1979&nbsp;<br>
      at the noted Tashing yard, Taiwan.&nbsp;She is a long-keeled, heavy displacement
      cutter intended for offshore passage-making and at home in heavy weather.</font></p>
      <p align="left"><font face="Comic Sans MS">Ian Laval, an English furnituremaker<br>
    and journalist, has owned her since 1999 when he arrived in north America looking for a
      tough, comfortable and roomy boat to sail to Europe.</font></p>
      <p align="left"><font face="Comic Sans MS">She is heavily constructed in
      glass-fibre with teak decks and exceptionally high-quality Burma <br>
    teak joinery below.</font></p>
      <p align="left"><font face="Comic Sans MS">Ian Laval chose the Baba after an Atlantic crossing in a different boat. He sailed from Vancouver Island in
      Lydia B in summer 2001, going north up the Inside Passage&nbsp;to the Alaska border, out to British Columbia's Queen Charlotte Islands
      then south down the Pacific past the United States, Central America,
      through the Panama Canal, across the Caribbean, up the US east coast and
      across the Atlantic via the Azores to northwest England in summer 2003.
      Lydia B performed faultlessly on the 15,000nm cruise.</font></p>
